| population_metro                = \n| population_density_km2          = 583.91\n| population_density_sq_mi        = 1512.35\n<!-- General information  -->| timezone                        = [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific (PST)]]\n| utc_offset                      = -8\n| timezone_DST                    = PDT\n| utc_offset_DST                  = -7\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|46|8|31|N|122|54|22|W|region:US-WA|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation_footnotes             = <!--for references: use <ref> tags-->\n| elevation_m                     = 23\n| elevation_ft                    = 75\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code                     = 98626\n| area_code                       = 360\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 53-35065\n| blank1_name                     = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info                     = 1512343<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=January 31, 2008|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=October 25, 2007}}</ref>\n| website                         = {{URL|http://www.kelso.gov/|kelso.gov}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| name                            = \n}}\n\n'''Kelso''' is a city in the southwestern part of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] and is the county seat of [[Cowlitz County, Washington|Cowlitz County]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=June 7, 2011|title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=May 31, 2011}}</ref>  At the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], the population was 11,925.  Kelso is part of the [[Longview, Washington]] [[Metropolitan Statistical Area]], which has a population of 102,410.  Kelso shares its long western border with Longview.  It is near [[Mount St. Helens]].\n\n==History==\nThe earliest known inhabitants of Kelso were [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] from the [[Cowlitz people|Cowlitz tribe]]. The Cowlitz people were separated into the Upper (or Taidnapam) and Lower (or Mountain) Cowlitz tribes, who were members of the [[Sahaptin]] and [[Salishan languages|Salish]] language families, respectively.  In 1855,  European explorers noted that there numbered over 6000 individuals of the Cowlitz Tribe.\n\nKelso was founded by [[Peter Crawford (land surveyor)|Peter W. Crawford]], a Scottish surveyor, who, in 1847, took up the first donation land claim on the Lower [[Cowlitz River]].  Crawford platted a townsite which he named after his home town of [[Kelso, Scottish Borders|Kelso]], [[Scotland]]. The original plat was dated and filed in October 1884.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Meany |first= Edmond S. |authorlink= Edmond S. Meany |year= 1920 |title= Origin of Washington Geographic Names |journal= The Washington Historical Quarterly |volume= XI |page= 44 |publisher= Washington University State Historical Society |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=dbsUAAAAYAAJ |accessdate=June 11, 2009}}</ref>  It became incorporated in 1889.\n\nIn its early days, Kelso obtained the nickname \"Little Chicago\" as it became famous for its large number of [[tavern]]s and [[brothel]]s that catered to local [[loggers]]. On weekends, trainloads of loggers would come into town from the surrounding region looking for women, liquor, gambling and fights. The [[FBI]] finally forced the mayor to shut them down in the 1950s with the last closing in the mid-1960s.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.tdn.com/articles/2009/05/24/top_story/doc4a177571a2f4a525663283.txt| title=Four Things That Helped Define Kelso | newspaper=The Daily News | author=Amy Fischer | date=May 24, 2009|accessdate=November 2, 2009}}</ref>  The economy continues to be based largely on wood products.\n\nIn the late 19th century and into the first part of the 20th century, Kelso was the center for commercial [[Eulachon|smelt]] fishing on the Cowlitz River.  In 1910, according to the Oregonian Newspaper, 5,000 tons of fish were caught.<ref>{{cite news | url= | title=Smelt Fishing on the Cowlitz: How an Army of Men Catch the Biggest Run Known in the Last Twenty Years | publisher=The Sunday Oregonian | author=R.G. Callvert | date=February 27, 1910 | accessdate=}}</ref>  The Kelso Chamber of Commerce created the slogan in 1956 and became known as the Smelt Capital of the World.<ref>[http://www.co.cowlitz.wa.us/tourism/brochure/Read%202003/2003%20Kelso%20SPREAD.pdf Co.cowlitz.wa.us] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719115726/http://www.co.cowlitz.wa.us/tourism/brochure/Read%202003/2003%20Kelso%20SPREAD.pdf |date=2011-07-19 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.cbr.washington.edu/shadfoundation/smelt/smelt11-20.pdf CBR.washington.edu] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215071733/http://www.cbr.washington.edu/shadfoundation/smelt/smelt11-20.pdf |date=2010-02-15 }}</ref>  The Cowlitz River has historically had heavy runs of smelt and were shipped to markets around the country. Smelt numbers have declined significantly in the past several decades possibly due to [[overharvesting]], global [[climate change]] and [[habitat loss]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cbbulletin.com/Free/265113.aspx| title=NOAA Accepts Petition For Listing Columbia River Basin Smelt  | publisher=The Columbia Basin Fish & Wildlife News Bulletin | author= |date=March 14, 2008|accessdate=September 11, 2009}}</ref>\n\nPieces of the mysterious 1947 [[Maury Island incident]] took place in Kelso.  A military aircraft carrying suspicious [[slag]]-like material, supposedly from a [[UFO]], crashed in southeast Kelso.\n\nOn May 18, 1980, being only {{convert|24|mi|km}} away, Kelso residents experienced the shock wave caused by the eruption of [[Mt. St. Helens]]. Called the largest volcanic eruption in historic times in the contiguous United States,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://encarta.msn.com/sidebar_761593956/The_Eruption_of_Washington_State's_Mount_St_Helens.html |title=The Eruption of Washington State's Mount St. Helens |newspaper=The Los Angeles Times |author=Gaylord Shaw |date=May 19, 1980 |accessdate=September 12, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kwsDei7C?url=http://encarta.msn.com/sidebar_761593956/The_Eruption_of_Washington_State%5C%27s_Mount_St_Helens.html |archivedate=November 1, 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Kelso received large amounts of [[volcanic ash]] through the air and from the massive mudflow caused by the eruption transported by the [[Toutle River|Toutle]] and Cowlitz Rivers.  Many areas of the city, including the Three Rivers Golf Course are built on volcanic ash<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.elks.org/Lodges/LodgeFacilities.cfm?LodgeNumber=1482| title=Kelso/Longview, WA #1482 | publisher=Elks| author=| date=| accessdate=September 12, 2009}}</ref> dredged from the Cowlitz River by inmates in state custody and volunteers.\n\nIn March 1998, the [[Aldercrest-Banyon landslide]] began shifting the foundations of 64 homes and local infrastructure in the east Kelso neighborhood of Aldercrest.  Eventually, 129 houses were destroyed by this slow moving landslide. Investigation showed that these houses had been built on top of an ancient active [[landslide]] area, and three straight years of higher than average rains set the earth into motion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mst.edu/~rogersda/professional_experience/aldercrest-banyon_ls.htm|title=Aldercrest-Banyon Landslide Kelso, WA - J. David Rogers|website=web.mst.edu}}</ref>\nIn October 1998, President [[Bill Clinton]] declared this slide a federal disaster.  It was the second worst landslide disaster (in cost) in the United States, following the 1956 [[Portuguese Bend|Portuguese Bend Landslide]] on [[Palos Verdes Hills]] in Southern California.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://slidingthought.wordpress.com/2009/07/29/landslide-of-the-week-aldercrest-banyon-landslide/| title=Landslide of the Week \u2013 Aldercrest Banyon Landslide  | publisher=Washington's Landslide Blog| author= | date=July 27, 2009| accessdate=September 12, 2009}}</ref> This disaster at Aldercrest led to stricter city [[zoning]] ordinances and oversight over geological surveys.\n\nThe [[Cowlitz County Historical Museum]] provides many exhibits on the history of the local area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.co.cowlitz.wa.us/museum/|title=Cowlitz County, WA - Official Website - Museum|website=www.co.cowlitz.wa.us}}</ref>\n\n===National Register of Historic Places===\n* Adam Catlin House\n* Nat Smith House\n* US Post Office - Kelso Main<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nrhp.focus.nps.gov/natreghome.do|title=National Register of Historic Places|publisher=National Park Service| author= | date= |accessdate=July 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nKelso is located on [[Interstate 5]] at Exits 36, 39, 40 and 42, and is {{convert|48|mi|km}} north of [[Portland, Oregon]], {{convert|125|mi|km}} south of [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]], and {{convert|80|mi|km}} from the Pacific Ocean beaches.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|8.50|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which, {{convert|8.14|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.36|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=December 19, 2012|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702145235/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=July 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThree rivers, the [[Columbia River|Columbia]], Cowlitz and [[Coweeman River|Coweeman]], running through Kelso were used as part of a historical transportation route from Portland, Oregon and the [[Puget Sound]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sos.wa.gov/History/cities_detail.aspx?i=40| title=A History of Cowlitz County| publisher=Washington Secretary of State | author= | date=| accessdate=February 6, 2010}}</ref> [[Steamboats of the Cowlitz River|Cowlitz steamboats]] were used as a source of transportation until 1918.\n\nKelso and Longview comprise the \"Twin Cities\" of southwest Washington.\n\n===Climate===\n{{Weather box \n|location = [[Southwest Washington Regional Airport]]\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F = 61\n|Feb record high F = 70\n|Mar record high F = 77\n|Apr record high F = 86\n|May record high F = 99\n|Jun record high F = 97\n|Jul record high F = 106\n|Aug record high F = 99\n|Sep record high F = 94\n|Oct record high F = 86\n|Nov record high F = 69\n|Dec record high F = 63\n|year record high F= \n|Jan high F = 41.2\n|Feb high F = 48.1\n|Mar high F = 51.6\n|Apr high F = 61.5\n|May high F = 66.3\n|Jun high F = 70.6\n|Jul high F = 76.3\n|Aug high F = 76.5\n|Sep high F = 74.9\n|Oct high F = 61.9\n|Nov high F = 52.5\n|Dec high F = 46.5\n|Jan low F = 28.9\n|Feb low F = 33.2\n|Mar low F = 34.9\n|Apr low F = 36.8\n|May low F = 42.1\n|Jun low F = 47.2\n|Jul low F = 50.0\n|Aug low F = 50.6\n|Sep low F = 46.0\n|Oct low F = 40.3\n|Nov low F = 36.7\n|Dec low F = 35.4\n|Jan record low F = -1\n|Feb record low F = 2\n|Mar record low F = 18\n|Apr record low F = 27\n|May record low F = 30\n|Jun record low F = 35\n|Jul record low F = 39\n|Aug record low F = 37\n|Sep record low F = 32\n|Oct record low F = 21\n|Nov record low F = 13\n|Dec record low F = 16\n|year record low F= \n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation inch = 6.27\n|Feb precipitation inch = 5.47\n|Mar precipitation inch = 5.82\n|Apr precipitation inch = 2.48\n|May precipitation inch = 2.16\n|Jun precipitation inch = 1.83\n|Jul precipitation inch = 0.50\n|Aug precipitat